  "prompt": "What is the stock purchase plan for Tesla motors?",
  "response": "As of my last update, Tesla, Inc. (formerly Tesla Motors) offers various stock purchase plans that allow employees and investors to buy shares in the company. Here's an overview of the typical options available:\n\n### Employee Stock Purchase Plan (ESPP)\n\n1. **Eligibility**: Typically, regular full-time and part-time employees are eligible to participate.\n2. **Offering Periods**: These are usually set for specific durations, such as six months, during which employees can enroll and contribute.\n3. **Contribution**: Employees can contribute a percentage of their salary, often up to a certain limit (e.g., 10% of eligible compensation).\n4. **Purchase Price**: The purchase price is often discounted, typically around 15% off the lower of the stock price at the beginning or end of the offering period.\n5. **Purchase**: At the end of the offering period, the accumulated contributions are used to purchase Tesla stock at the discounted price.\n\n### Direct Stock Purchase Plan (DSPP)\n\n1. **Eligibility**: Generally available to any investor, not just employees.\n2. **Brokerage**: Investors can purchase Tesla stock directly through a brokerage that offers a DSPP.\n3. **Dividend Reinvestment**: Some DSPPs allow investors to automatically reinvest dividends to purchase additional shares.\n4. **Fees**: There may be fees associated with enrollment, purchases, and sales.\n\n### Stock Options\n\n1. **Employee Stock Options (ESOs)**: These are often part of employee compensation packages, giving employees the right to buy Tesla stock at a predetermined price (strike price) within a certain period.\n2. **Incentive Stock Options (ISOs) and Non-Qualified Stock Options (NSOs)**: ISOs have tax advantages but come with more restrictions, whereas NSOs are more flexible but taxed as ordinary income.\n\n### Public Trading\n\n1. **Open Market**: Anyone can buy Tesla stock through a standard brokerage account on stock exchanges like NASDAQ (TSLA).\n2. **Brokerage Services**: Various online and traditional brokerages offer platforms to buy and sell Tesla stock.\n\n### Additional Considerations\n\n- **Vesting**: For employee-related stock plans, there may be a vesting period before the shares or options can be fully owned or exercised.\n- **Tax Implications**: The tax treatment of stock purchases can vary significantly based on the type of plan and local tax laws.\n\nFor the most current and detailed information, it's advisable to:\n\n1. **Consult Tesla\u2019s Official Resources**: Check Tesla's investor relations website or their latest proxy statement for the most current details on their stock purchase plans.\n2. **Employee Resources**: If you're an employee, refer to your employee handbook or HR department for specifics on the ESPP and other employee-related plans.\n3. **Financial Advisor**: Consider speaking with a financial advisor to understand the implications and best strategies for participating in these plans.\n\nPlease note that stock plans and their specifics can change, so always verify the information with the latest resources available from Tesla.",
